11282nam a2201309Ia 9780774869058DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748690587 a10.59962/97807748690582doi  a(DE-B1597)678824  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aGC1023.15b.S43 2024 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a333.91/64160971223/eng/2023102300aSea Change :bCharting a Sustainable Future for Oceans in Canada /ced. by Ussif Rashid Sumaila, William Cheung, Megan Bailey, Derek Armitage. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b7 b&w photos, 19 tables, 17 charts, 9 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSustainability and the Environment00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPART 1 Setting the Stage -- t1 A Partnership Approach to the Study of Canada’s Oceans and Coasts -- t2 Status of Reconciliation and Indigenous Ocean Management in Canada -- tPART 2 Changing Oceans -- t3 Rapid Changes across Canada’s Oceans and Their Impact on Coastal Communities -- t4 Large Changes in Canada’s Oceans and Their Impacts on Ecosystems and Fisheries -- t5 Using Multiscale Scenarios to Investigate the Outlook for Marine Ecosystems and Coastal Communities -- tPART 3 Access to Ocean Resources -- t6 Lobsters and Livelihoods: Indigenous Rights and Fishery Access -- t7 The Impact of Quotas on Canada’s Fisheries and the Response of Fish Harvesters -- t8 The Role of Fisheries Co-Management in Addressing Access and Allocation Inequities in Eastern Inuit Nunangat -- tPART 4 Ocean Governance -- t9 Transforming the Governance of Canada’s Oceans and Coasts from the Bottom Up -- t10 Knowledge Co-Production and Enhanced Governance Fit in Rebuilding Canada’s Coastal Fisheries -- t11 Bright Spots in Integrated Management of Canada’s Oceans and Coasts -- tPART 5 Into the Future -- t12 Progress and Challenges in Making Canada’s Ocean Laws and Policies Climate-Ready -- t13 Coastlines, Communities, and Cameras: How Participatory Video Can Enhance Ocean Research -- t14 Policy Direction for Reconciliation and Indigenous Ocean Management in Canada -- t15 Toward a Healthy Future for Canada’s Oceans and Coasts -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs climate change, resource overexploitation, and pollution leave ever more visible marks, ocean ecosystems, economies, and people are all affected. With coasts on the Atlantic, Pacific, and Arctic, Canada faces a formidable challenge in building resilient, sustainable oceans and supporting the communities that rely on them. Sea Change reports on the OceanCanada Partnership, a multidisciplinary project to take stock of what we know about Canada’s oceans, construct possible scenarios for coastal regions, and create a national dialogue and vision. Three themes emerge from this impressive synthesis of social, cultural, economic, and environmental research: ocean change, access to ocean resources, and ocean governance. Indigenous and non-Indigenous scholars and practitioners focus on finding solutions to rapid environmental and social transformation, outlining the implications for legislation and offering policy recommendations. Increasingly, civil society will have to advocate for oceans, and Sea Change will empower the voices of those who take up that task.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMarine ecologyzCanada. 0aMarine ecosystem managementzCanada. 0aMarine resources conservationzCanada. 0aOceanzCanada. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 a. Newell, Sarah L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat